{
  "texts": [
    "It is considered as a general term for a series of subjective cognitive experiences.",
    "However, there is no scientific agreement on a definition of emotions.",
    "It is defined as \"the bodily changes directly follow the perception of the exciting fact, and that our feelings of the changes as they occur\" by William James (1884, cited in [14]) while Ekman et al. [45] define it as a \"human's state of mind and feelings, including psychological, physical and social aspects\".",
    "The affective state is used as a more common term by researchers for emotional states [1].Fig. 1 The international 10/20 system [41] Various models have been proposed in the literature to classify and represent emotions and as in the definition of emotion, there is no consensus on a general model as well [42].",
    "These are categorical models in which discrete definitions are determined for each emotion while the other is dimensional models in which emotions are classified based on dimensional scales [46,47]."
  ]
}